trates how major debates on UN peace operations - on civilian protection, local ownership, or gender mainstreaming - benefit from theoretical exploration. With insightful contributions from a range of international academics, UN peace operations and International Relations theory is an essential book for scholars, students, and experts working on peace and security and the broader issue of international cooperation.This book is relevant to United Nations Sustainable Development Goal 16, Peace, justice and strong institutions  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational relationsxPhilosophy. 4aInternational Relations 2020. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aInternational Relations theory.  aPeace, justice and strong institutions.  aUnited Nations.  acomplexity theory.  aconstructivism.  acritical security studies.  ainstitutionalism.  apeace operations.  apeacekeeping.  apractice theory.  arealism.1 aBerdal, Mats, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBode, Ingvild, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCunliffe, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Georgina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHunt, Charles T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarlsrud, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarlsrud, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLaurence, Marion, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaertens, Lucile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonteleone, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOks